Let’s pretend that the S-node is our start node, and all edges are directed down
A common upper-bound heuristic is the greedy algorithm due to it’s simplicity and low memory/search requirements.
What we want from this is
a worst-case scenario that isn’t completely out to lunch
We don’t just store the cost, but also the full solution, so that we can seed our search space.
The start node is at the bottom of the stack, and the final node is at the top.
Branch means that we produce a list of candidate nodes. These are child nodes that have not yet been evaluated
Bound means we determine the bound on each of the candidate nodes
The lower bound is the best-possible solution that this candidate node can produce, so if the node’s best-possible is worse than our best-so-far, we won’t waste compute-power evaluating its children.
he main differences are that A*
Uses a heap to track the lowest heuristic/distance combination
It only pushes the root node into the heap, rather than a heuristic solution
Admissible means that no candidates OVER-estimate their cost, so the true cost will always be greater.
This is required in order to meet A*’s extended list benefits

With A*, we don’t have any solution until we finish our search. With Branch and Bound’s heuristic solution and iterative shallowing, we can bail out if we run out of time where we may have found a solution somewhere between the heuristic and the optimal

Because we’re using a stack instead of a heap, and we don’t need to maintain a list of all of the frontier nodes, we will use less memory, and we will have fewer page faults from bouncing around trying to re-order our heap.
